    "review::.::holistic::error_consistency::provider_config_broad_catch": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::error_consistency::provider_config_broad_catch",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 1,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "ProviderConfigController catches bare Exception for config-building methods, masking programming errors alongside expected config failures",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "error_consistency",
        "related_files": [
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/controller/ProviderConfigController.java"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "Lines 43 and 50 catch Exception broadly on buildGoogleConfig() and buildMicrosoftConfig(). These methods only throw implicitly (e.g., NPE from null properties, or runtime exceptions from Spring config).",
          "If a NullPointerException from a coding bug occurs, it is silently caught and the provider is returned as disabled, making the bug invisible to developers and hard to diagnose in production.",
          "The error is logged, but the catch scope is too broad \u2014 it should catch specific exceptions or at least not catch Error subclasses"
        ],
        "suggestion": "Narrow the catch to RuntimeException at minimum, or better yet, identify the specific exceptions these builders can throw and catch only those. Consider letting programming errors (NPE, ClassCast) propagate to the GlobalExceptionHandler.",
        "reasoning": "",
        "summary_hash": "35d73f20"
      },
      "status": "wontfix",
      "note": "All three are significant architectural changes requiring new test infrastructure or fundamental provider wiring redesign \u2014 beyond code quality improvement scope",
