    "review::.::holistic::mid_level_elegance::ms_challenge_inline_orchestration": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::mid_level_elegance::ms_challenge_inline_orchestration",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 2,
      "confidence": "medium",
      "summary": "AuthController.verifyMicrosoftToken mixes cookie extraction, nonce lifecycle, and token verification in one method rather than composing distinct collaborators",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "mid_level_elegance",
        "related_files": [
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/controller/AuthController.java"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "verifyMicrosoftToken (~30 LOC) handles: (1) rollout check, (2) verifier availability, (3) request validation, (4) cookie extraction via currentChallengeSessionId, (5) nonce consumption via microsoftChallengeStore.consumeNonce, (6) token verification, (7) auth completion. The cookie-session concern (steps 4-5) is infrastructure-level glue that obscures the orchestration logic.",
          "issueMicrosoftChallenge similarly handles session-cookie creation inline. The cookie lifecycle management (createChallengeSessionCookie, currentChallengeSessionId) is an infrastructure concern mixed into the controller orchestration layer."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Extract a MicrosoftChallengeSessionService that owns the cookie-to-nonce lifecycle. AuthController would call challengeSessionService.resolveNonce(request, challengeId) and receive either a nonce or an error, making the controller read as pure orchestration of collaborators.",
