        "scan_count": 7,
        "tier": 2,
        "confidence": "medium",
        "detail": {
          "holistic": true,
          "dimension": "authorization_consistency",
          "related_files": [
            "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/config/SecurityConfig.java"
          ],
          "evidence": [
            "In SecurityConfig.filterChain(), CSRF is disabled via ignoringRequestMatchers(\"/auth/google/verify\", \"/auth/microsoft/*\", \"/auth/exchange\", \"/auth/logout\"). The /auth/microsoft/* pattern only matches one path segment (e.g., /auth/microsoft/verify, /auth/microsoft/challenge) while the authorization rule uses /auth/** which matches all depths. This is functionally correct today since Microsoft endpoints are exactly one level deep, but the inconsistent wildcard style (/microsoft/* vs /**) could lead to a gap if a nested endpoint is added."
          ],
          "suggestion": "Either enumerate Microsoft endpoints explicitly (matching the Google and Exchange style) for maximum clarity, or use /auth/microsoft/** for consistency with the permitAll pattern. Explicit enumeration is safer: ignoringRequestMatchers(\"/auth/google/verify\", \"/auth/microsoft/challenge\", \"/auth/microsoft/verify\", \"/auth/exchange\", \"/auth/logout\").",
          "reasoning": "",
          "summary_hash": "891043e4"
        }
      }
    },
    "review::.::holistic::authorization_consistency::logout_no_server_side_revocation": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::authorization_consistency::logout_no_server_side_revocation",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "low",
      "summary": "POST /auth/logout returns success but performs no server-side JWT invalidation or token blocklisting",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "authorization_consistency",
        "related_files": [
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/controller/AuthController.java"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "AuthController.logout() simply returns ResponseEntity.ok(new LogoutResponse(\"Logged out successfully\")) with no server-side action \u2014 no token blocklist check, no Redis expiry, no SecurityContext clearing. The frontend removes the JWT from localStorage, but the token remains cryptographically valid until expiry (86400000ms = 24 hours). A stolen token continues to work even after the user 'logs out'."
        ],
        "suggestion": "If full revocation is not needed, add a brief Javadoc comment on the logout method documenting the design decision (stateless JWT, client-side only, no revocation). If revocation is desired, implement a Redis-backed token blocklist and check it in JwtAuthenticationFilter.validateAndExtract(). The documentation approach is the simpler and likely appropriate path for this experimental project.",
        "reasoning": "",
        "summary_hash": "78e69326"
      },
      "status": "wontfix",
      "note": "All three are significant architectural changes requiring new test infrastructure or fundamental provider wiring redesign \u2014 beyond code quality improvement scope",
